# Linux Special Permissions

## SUID

Runs programs with the owner's privileges.

Example:

```bash
ls -l /usr/bin/passwd
```

---

## SGID

Allows files to inherit group ownership and programs to run with group privileges.

---

## Sticky Bit

Protects files in shared directories by allowing only the owner to delete their files.

Example:

```bash
ls -ld /tmp
```

---

## Why These Permissions Matter

- Improve security
- Enable controlled privilege escalation
- Support secure collaboration
- Protect shared directories
